      Introduction¶

      In this project we will introduce to some of machine learning methods including KNN Regressor, Linear Regression, Decision Tree Regressor, Random Forest Regressor and Voting Regressor.
      In the 1st step we will examine and anylize the dataset. 2nd step is preprocess. In the 3d step we train individual models. And in last step we will try ensemble regressors.

      Project description¶

      We have a dataset including attributes of houses and their prices. Number of attributes is 82. We are to predict test houses which their attributes are new to our models.

      When the values of output and other attributes did not have linear relationship (Like exponensial relationship) by applying log transformation, relationship of them become linear. In fact by applying log transformation we can respond to skewness towards large values. Linear relationships are much easier for models to learn.

      1. Some attributes are a refering to a same concept and are actually same variable. It is not essential to keep them both.<br> For example we can see both 'GarageCars' and 'GarageArea' have high correlation with 'SalePrice' but they are actually describing same thing. So it is good to omit one of them. I prefer to omit 'GarageCars' because it seems that 'GarageArea' can give the model more information to learn comparitively.<br> Another example is 'TotalBsmtSF' and '1stFlrSF' which seem to be same. I choose 'TotalBsmtSF' because I think it give our model more information.
      2
      ​
      3
      2. Sometimes correlation of 2 attributes is high because of specific distribution of those attributes. For example in uniform distribution based on its parameter, it is possible to get high correlation. But actualy they are not closely related.
      4
      ​
      5
      3. It is possible that some attributes have considerable outliers. This can reduce accuracy of the model. It is good to remove them.

      1. Some attributes are a refering to a same concept and are actually same variable. It is not essential to keep them both.
        For example we can see both 'GarageCars' and 'GarageArea' have high correlation with 'SalePrice' but they are actually describing same thing. So it is good to omit one of them. I prefer to omit 'GarageCars' because it seems that 'GarageArea' can give the model more information to learn comparitively.
        Another example is 'TotalBsmtSF' and '1stFlrSF' which seem to be same. I choose 'TotalBsmtSF' because I think it give our model more information.

      2. Sometimes correlation of 2 attributes is high because of specific distribution of those attributes. For example in uniform distribution based on its parameter, it is possible to get high correlation. But actualy they are not closely related.

      3. It is possible that some attributes have considerable outliers. This can reduce accuracy of the model. It is good to remove them.

      1. To extract usefull categorical attributes first we calculate average of 'SalePrice' for every possible value of all categorical attributes. It helps us to recognize important attributes.
        In attributes which have great impact on house prices, there is high variance among averages for possible values.
        In those attributes with less impact differences of averages for possible values is low and they are less usefull for model to learn the train data. In fact they dont give our model something big to learn.
        Attributes of 'ExterQual', 'KitchenQual' and 'BsmtQual' have big variance among all attributes. It means that they have big impact on sale price and are more likely to be useful for our model to learn from them.
        Their plots illustrated bellow.

      There are 3 main methods for handling missing data.
      2
      1. Deletion of missing data of dataset: In small datasets it's not good idea to use this method. It may decrease accuracy thereupon. But if the dataset is huge it is fine to use this method specially if missing values are in identical rows. There are two main techniques for deletion of data when we observe missing data. data listwise and dropping variables. Usage of these techniques is based on type of missing values.
      3
      ​
      4
      2. Replacement with statistical values: In this method missing values will be replaced with statistical values like mean, median or mode. Choosing between mean and median and mode depends on distribution of values in dataset. For example If we have fairly high number of outliers or noises in our dataset It is better to use replacement with median rather than mean. Because noises can highly affect the mean value. Replacement of missing values with statistical values is good because the missing values are replacing with a ratunal value. Replaced values does not cause the output to deviate and Also does not give the model something important to learn.
      5
      ​
      6
      3. Model-based methods.: In this method for example if we have missing values in in a feature we assume this feature as output and give other features as our inputs to a training model. Then we predict the missing ones. By having missing values in a number of features his method could takes more time and calculational effort than other methods because we need to run the model for each feature. In huge datasets this method takes a lot of time. But we have chance of getting more accuracy. This is a trade-off.
      7
      ​
      8
      4. Some models in machine learning like KNN can work with missing values. In fact it is not necessary to handle missing values.

      Categorical attributes can be divided into different types.

      1. Binary: The categorical attribute of this type can take only 2 values. Like 0/1. True/False.

      2. Ordinal: The categorical attribute of this type can can take several values which have an order. Like very_good/good/bad/very_bad.

      3. Nominal: The categorical attribute of this type can can take several values which do not have any order. Like Male/Female.

      It is essential to encode categorical attributes. Because machine learning models can only work with numerical attributes.
      Based on type of a categorical attribute there are different encoding methods.

      • Binary encoding: This type of encoding is used in binary categorical attributes. Where 2 possible values are replaced by 0/1.

      • Ordinal Feature Encoding This type of encoding is used in ordinal categorical attributes. An order is considered for assigned numerical values based on the context of attribute. For example very_good/good/bad/very_bad values can be replaced by 1/2/3/4. (Integer encoding)

      • One-hot encoding For nominal categorical attributes One-hot encoding is more suitable. Because there is no order between different values considering numbers which have an order could cause the model to deviate and poor perforamance.
        In one hot encoding, a new binary variable is created for each possible value of each categorical attribute.
        One of problems of one-hot encoding is highly growing of size of dataframe. Another problem is that the dataframe is too sparse. Values in dataframe havo no semantic information.

      Chooseing a split percentage depends on the project’s objectives and its considerations. For example there is a trade-off between computational cost of training the model and computational cost of evaluating the model. We shoulde also notice that with less training data, we get greater variance and with less testing data, the performance statistic will have higher variance. We should choose the parameter p in a way that both variances are low. Specially if we have a small dataset, the variances are more likely to get high and we have to choose the parameter more precisely.<br>

      * Underfitting: <br>
      2
      Underfitting happens when a model can not properly model both training data and test data. In fact the model does not fit the data accurately and performance is poor. It usually happens when we have small data and it is not enough for our model to learn accurately. It is also possible that type of our model is not good for the data. For example choosing linear model for a data which is not linear could cause underfitting. Feature selection can be effective too. <br>
      3
      Underfitted model is high biased and have low variance.<br>
      4
      To avoid underfitting we can do several things, Like increasing complexity, increasing features (in feature selection) and removing noise from data.<br>
      5
      <br>
      6
      * Overfitting: <br>
      7
      Overfitting happens when a model is too good at modeling train data But have poor performance on test data. A overfitted model learns details and noise from training data and because of that modeling train data is too good. But impact its performance on test data. Overfitting usually happens in non-linear and non-parametric models. Becuase they are flexible to learn details of training data and overfit. <br>
      8
      Overfitted model is low biased and have high variance.<br>
      9
      To avoid underfitting we can do several things, Like increasing size of train data, decreasing complexity and early stoppings during learning phase.

      ### 3

      3¶

      x
      1
      Voting regressor has better results in comparison with knn, linear regression and decision tree.<br>
      2
      Voting regression is and ensemble model which combine multiple models and their predictions and prepare the final prediction(by averaging).In voting regression by combining multiple models, we can get a model with appropriate performance and accuracy with less need for tuning hyper parameters. One of the advantages of ensemble models is generalization which makes them powerful to predict unseen datasets. In fact in these models errors of individual regressors can be corrected.<br>
      3
      These are the reasons why we get lower error in voting regressor.
